    <text>
        <body>
      
		<pb n="1"/>
			<p><hi rend="underline">German and Yiddish</hi></p>
          <p rend="indent(9)"><placeName>N.Y.</placeName> <date>Friday Pericofe <add>&#63;</add></date></p>
          <p rend="indent(8)"><del>&#40;<date>December</date>&#41;</del> <date>February 1849</date>.</p>
			<p><addressee>Revd. Leeser</addressee>&#44; <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>&#58;</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">In the last number of the &#8220;Occident&#44;&#8221;<lb/> I notice an article signed with the name &#8220;<persName>Ayala<lb/> Sh&#39;lucha</persName>&#8221; &#40; &#41;. I also noticed my name mentioned<lb/> in an article in the last number of your valued<lb/> magazine&#44; with the signature &#8220;Ayala Sh&#39;lucha&#8221;<lb/> &#40;in connection with this one may well add the closing<lb/> phrase&#44; &#8220;Who gives forth beautiful words&#8221;&#41;&#42;. For<lb/> this mention I want to express my thanks to you<lb/> for your defense of me against the attacks in<lb/> certain <del>?</del> issues of the &#8220;Hasmonean&#8221;.<lb/> It was at this time that I first became<lb/> aware that you are the second one who did not<lb/> overlook <del>my</del> the insult to me. You were<lb/> good enough to send the number containing<lb/> your defense&#44; whereas the first one who de&#45;<lb/>fended me in the &#8220;Hasmonean&#44;&#8221; signed with the<lb/> name &#8220;<persName>Ashkenazi</persName>&#44;&#8221;still remains unknown<lb/> to me. Just why you as well the other fighter<lb/> preferred to remain unknown&#44; I cannot<lb/> explain. The men of action and pious people<lb/> of old used to sign their names openly in<lb/> the course of a struggle. If I did not</p>
			<p>&#42;Genesis 49.21</p>
		<pb n="2"/>
			<p>thank you until now&#44; it is because I was<lb/> afraid of hurting your feelings&#44; but I have<lb/> always valued your attitude. That I want<lb/> you to know&#44; since your magazine takes the<lb/> middle road as its tendency. I repeat what<lb/> I have once remarked to you that it<lb/> would be much more useful for your<lb/> magazine to be a weekly instead of a<lb/> monthly.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">Along with this&#44; I want to ask you<lb/> to include in the next number the following<lb/> notice&#44; &#8220;Ethrogim and Lulabim From <placeName>Italy</placeName>&#44;<lb/> as a Title&#44; from <persName>C. Nussbaum</persName>&#44; <placeName>187 Rivington<lb/> St.</placeName> are to be had Settrogim and lulabim<lb/> from <placeName>Italy</placeName>.</p>
			<p rend="align(center)"><hi rend="underline">German Advertisement</hi></p>
			<p><add>Double lines inserted here to divide letter from the following</add></p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">If you can send me your prayer&#45;<lb/>books of the German ritual and the pentateuchs&#44;<lb/> unbound at a low price&#44; I should like to<lb/> order some from you. Please let me know the<lb/> exact price of the above&#44; both cheaply and<lb/> elegantly bound.</p>
		<pb n="3"/>
          <p rend="indent(6)">Respectfully&#44;</p>
          <p rend="indent(7)"><persName role="author">C. Nussbaum</persName></p>
			<p>Since I cannot obtain a number of<lb/> your magazine&#44; please do not forget it<lb/> or put it aside&#44; so that it might be left<lb/> out. If you would order something for me&#44;<lb/> or use your influence in my favor&#44;<lb/> I shall be obliged to you.</p>

          
        </body>
